    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "## Problem\n\n\nSince 'autoread' gained filewatcher behavior https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/37971 , there is a potentially bad UX: if a user has unsaved changes in many files (e.g. after a LSP \"rename\" action), and lots of files also have external changes (e.g. from an AI agent), this [will prompt the user](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/37971#issuecomment-4658051311) with a cascade of \"W12\" warnings.\n\n```\nW12: Warning: File \"lua/guh/comments.lua\" has changed and the buffer was changed in Vim as well\nSee \":help W12\" for more info.\n[O]K, (L)oad File, Load File (a)nd Options:\n```\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nProvide a `(A)ll` action in the dialog so the user can accept (or reject...) all pending 'autoread' file-updates.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "There are two separate issues here:\n\n1. **Nested/stacked prompts**  \n   Autoread currently schedules one `:checktime {bufnr}` per watcher event. Although `checktime()` is synchronous, the W12 dialog waits through the command-line input loop, which processes `main_loop.events`. That means while prompt A is waiting for input, another scheduled autoread callback can run, call `:checktime {other_buf}`, and print prompt B on top of it.\n\n   So an “All” button alone is not enough if the other prompts are already printed before the first answer is received.\n\n2. **Too many sequential prompts**  \n   Even after preventing nesting, multiple changed/modified buffers would still prompt one-by-one unless the dialog has an “all” action.\n\nSuggested fixes:\n1. Coalesce watcher events and run one timestamp-check pass, instead of scheduling independent `:checktime {bufnr}` calls. In theory, `:checktime` without args would be that, but right now it only processes buffers inside visible windows (semantic difference vs current autoread implementation that includes hidden buffers also). This is on Lua side, in `runtime/lua/nvim/autoread.lua`.\n2. Actually add “Load All” / “Keep All” in W12 dialog (note, just `(A)ll` alone is not enough - \"all what? load or keep?\"), which would then apply user's choice to all buffers in the loop, in a single prompt. The loop is in check_timestamps() function, on C side. `src/nvim/fileio.c:2813`",
            "created_at": "2026-06-15T19:04:46Z",
